---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import { withBase } from "../../utils/url";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Quickstart"
  description="Get a working dbt pipeline where a Python model runs on Burla in under 5 minutes."
  lede="The shortest path from nothing to 'I saw a dbt Python model run on Burla'. Two paths — one needs no cloud, one connects to your real warehouse."
  prev={{ title: "Overview", href: withBase("/docs/") }}
  next={{ title: "How it works", href: withBase("/docs/how-it-works/") }}
>
  <blockquote class="callout">
    <strong>Goal:</strong> get a working dbt pipeline where a Python model runs on Burla. In under 5 minutes. No cluster required.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Option A: zero-setup (DuckDB + fake Burla)</h2>

  <p>No cluster, no cloud, just <code>pip</code> and <code>dbt run</code>.</p>

  <Code
    code={`git clone https://github.com/Burla-Cloud/dbt-burla.git
cd dbt-burla/examples/01-quickstart-duckdb
pip install "dbt-burla[duckdb]"
dbt run --profiles-dir .`}
    lang="bash"
    theme="github-dark-dimmed"
  />

  <p>That's it. You now have three models in <code>warehouse.duckdb</code>:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>stg_orders</code> — a SQL view</li>
    <li><code>enriched_orders</code> — a Python model that runs in-process (because <code>burla_fake: true</code>)</li>
    <li><code>order_summary</code> — a downstream SQL aggregate</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Open the warehouse:</p>

  <Code
    code={`duckdb warehouse.duckdb
> select * from main.enriched_orders;`}
    lang="bash"
    theme="github-dark-dimmed"
  />

  <h2>Option B: real Burla cluster + your warehouse</h2>

  <h3>1. Install</h3>
  <Code code={`pip install "dbt-burla[snowflake]"   # or [bigquery] / [duckdb]`} lang="bash" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <h3>2. Configure Burla</h3>
  <Code code={`burla login`} lang="bash" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <h3>3. Point profiles.yml at dbt-burla</h3>
  <p>
    Every field your existing <code>dbt-snowflake</code> / <code>dbt-bigquery</code> / <code>dbt-duckdb</code> profile uses
    still works — just change <code>type:</code> to the Burla variant and add the <code>burla_*</code> knobs.
  </p>

  <Code
    code={`my_project:
  target: prod
  outputs:
    prod:
      type: burla_snowflake        # was: snowflake
      account: "{{ env_var('SNOWFLAKE_ACCOUNT') }}"
      user: "{{ env_var('SNOWFLAKE_USER') }}"
      password: "{{ env_var('SNOWFLAKE_PASSWORD') }}"
      database: PROD_DB
      warehouse: PROD_WH
      schema: analytics
      threads: 4

      # Burla-specific
      burla_cluster_url: https://my-cluster.burla.dev
      burla_default_workers: 100
      burla_default_cpus_per_worker: 4`}
    lang="yaml"
    theme="github-dark-dimmed"
  />

  <h3>4. Write a Python model</h3>
  <Code
    code={`# models/enriched_orders.py
import pandas as pd
from burla import remote_parallel_map


def enrich(row: dict) -> dict:
    row["amount_cents"] = int((row["amount"] or 0) * 100)
    return row


def model(dbt, session):
    dbt.config(materialized="table")
    orders = dbt.ref("stg_orders")
    enriched = list(remote_parallel_map(enrich, orders.to_dict("records")))
    return pd.DataFrame(enriched)`}
    lang="python"
    theme="github-dark-dimmed"
  />

  <h3>5. Run it</h3>
  <Code code={`dbt run --select enriched_orders`} lang="bash" theme="github-dark-dimmed" />

  <p>
    Watch Burla spin up workers and run your model. The result lands as a normal table in Snowflake,
    which downstream SQL models can <code>ref()</code> like any other.
  </p>

